<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-008-122 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 588 839</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Nov 25 1991 v13 n47 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM tries for 32-bit edge; tool can port Windows 3.0 applicationsto OS/2.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Scannell, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM is giving the OS/2 2.0 operating system the ability to run theMicrosoft Windows 3.0 applications recompiled to run in 32-bitmode in an effort to lure developers away from its rivalMicrosoft, according to industry insiders.andP;  The new capability isintended to give developers an easy, fast path to upgradingexisting 16-bit Windows applications before Microsoft shipsWindows NT.andP;  IBM believes that the strategy gives developers thechance to be compatible with the huge base of Windows 3.0graphical user interface applications, take advantage of OS/2 2.0,and accomplish their applications upgrades with less work.andO;Microsoft's upgrade path, called Win32, uses extensions that willrequire current Windows applications to be rewritten for 32-bitoperations.andP;  Developers using OS/2 2.0 can concentrate on theinstalled Windows 3.0 base, rather than split their developmentefforts.andP;  IBM had no comment on the reports.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product development)Microsoft Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    IBM; MSFT.andO;Product:   OS/2 2.0 (Operating system) (Product development)Mirrors (Program development software) (Usage).andO;Topic:     32-BitProduct DevelopmentGraphical user interfaceInteroperabilityCompatible SoftwareCompetitionOperating systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>